      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0416">
               <p>Born to a schoolmaster in <placeName>Londonderry, Ireland</placeName>, Clarke
                  proved a self-directing student, building competency in many languages. He was
                  converted in <date when="1778">1778</date>, and joined a Methodist society. Within
                  a couple of years he was exhorting, and preached his first sermon in <date
                     when="1782-06">June 1782</date>. By this time he had gained <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s attention, was sent to
                  Kingswood for further study (but stayed only a month), and put into a circuit. He
                  was a frequent correspondent with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> through the latter&apos;s final decade, and rose to prominence
                  as both a scholar and leading figure in British Methodism after <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s death. In <date
                     when="1788">1788</date> Clarke married <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers0463.xml"/>Mary Cooke</persName>, another frequent
                  correspondent in <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                  />JW</persName>&apos;s last decades. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 225–26; <hi
                     rend="italic">Minutes</hi> (post-Wesley, <date when="1833">1833</date>),
                  7:222–25; <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Dictionary</hi>, 69.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
